A board member of the Nigeria Women Football League , Joe Amene, believed free scoring striker Monday Gift deserves a Super Falcons call up preparatory to the Women Africa Cup of Nations Cup in Morocco following her heroics at the on-going NWFL Premiership Super Six in Benin, The FC Robo loanee to Bayelsa Queens yesterday scored a brace against Edo Queens of Benin take her goal tally in the Super Six to six goals in three matches and a total nine goals in the season to move to the top of the goals’ scorer chart. Gift scored once against Rivers Angels as well as the competition’s first hat trick against Naija Ratels of Abuja as well as the brace against Edo Queens in the Bayelsa Queens 2-1 victory against the Edo team. “Monday Gift is the only Nigeria Women Football League player who is in top form and merits the Falcons first team invitation,” noted Amene who doubles as the General Co-ordinator of the NWFL Nationwide League,   Ten Hag insists on red-hot Osimhen for Man United     2023 World Championships: Nigeria rules Western Region…     Rangers coach lauds ‘superb’ Aribo despite Europa loss   Amene, added it was unacceptable that an in-form Monday Gift is overlooked by the national team selectors, adding the gal than some of the players being given prominence in the national senior team. “At the last edition of Aisha Buhari Cup in Lagos, last year, Gift Monday was one of the two home players that scored the two goals scored by Nigeria,” he further explained. “After the last Super Six, the player went on loan to the Rivers Angels of Port Harcourt to rescue the team to the CAF Women Champions League. “ Soon after this, the player played at the Betsy Obaseki Women’s Football Challenge, in Benin City, where she scored nine out of the total 12 goals scored by her team, FC Robo of Lagos,” noted Anene even as he called on Falcons’ handlers to have a rethink and invite Monday Gift for the pre-WAFCON camp. Meanwhile, Bayelsa Queens maintain the top spot after three games with maximum nine points but they have played a game more than second placed Nasarawa Amazons who have six points from two games. Today, Bayelsa Queens will trade tackles with Delta Queens who are yet to register a win or score a goal after three games, at the Samuel Ogbemudia Stadium while second-placed Nasarawa Amazons will face their stiffest challenge when they square up with reigning champions, Rivers Angels at the UNIBEN Sports Complex.